node.text:
Entrepreneur's @heyfeifer chats with Chef @priavanda, head chef and owner of NYC-restaurant @desigalli, about how she kept her restaurant open and launch two new businesses during lockdown.

PriaVanda is also featured at the Boost with Facebook Good Ideas Festival, a virtual celebration of small businesses. The Festival will offer inspiration and education for small businesses all over the world. You can learn more about it at Fb.com/goodideasfestival.

node.text:
We have all learned during the pandemic that anything can happen. So how can entrepreneurs stay alert — and stay ahead — of future problems big and small?

@nicolewalters, CEO and founder of @inheritlearning, chats with @travis.montaque, CEO and founder of @holler.io, about staying flexible and adapting to new opportunities. (Brought to you by @delltech)

node.title: Succeed by Staying Flexible in Business

node.text:
Many founders (if not all founders) experience self-doubt. So how do you keep going when the voices around you (and sometimes in your head) are telling you that you're on a fast track to failure?

@nicolewalters, founder and CEO of @inheritlearning, chats with @nicolegibbonsstyle, founder and CEO of @clarepaint, about overcoming self-doubt when starting a business. (Brought to you by @delltech)

node.title: Building Confidence While Building Your Business

node.text:
Keeping your team on the same page is critical to a company managing its resources and moving toward a common goal.

@nicolewalters, CEO and founder of @inheritlearning, chats with @mandisaprice, CEO and co-founder of @kanarysinc, about using technology to keep your team on the same page. (Brought to you by @delltech)

node.title: How to Use Technology to Keep Your Teams Connected

“By bringing in your dog, you are also bringing another side of yourself to work. And the tension is eased because there is always a little ball of fluff sitting right next to you, looking up, amazed at the work you are doing. node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Entrepreneur on July 21, 2021 tagging @kimperell. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '" Go With Your Gut. @KIMPERELL'.

node.text:
Top angel investor and serial entrepreneur @KimPerell tells us “I haven’t always listened to my gut, and I regret that. I used to make big decisions based on data and logic, and subconsciously override my inner voice.”

She explains that looking back, she could have avoided making big mistakes if she would have just trusted her gut.⁣ And like Kim, most of us have experienced this same situation.
⁣
What is your gut telling you? To chase that big dream, or finally start that side hustle you’ve always wanted? If this rings true for you, then we’ve got just the thing to help get you started: The Side Hustle Accelerator. 

Specifically designed for those looking to make the jump into entrepreneurship, our online course was developed with expert entrepreneur Kim Perell and will take you step-by-step through the process of starting a side hustle.

Don’t overthink it, just trust your gut. 👉🏻 Click the link in bio to get started!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Entrepreneur on July 20, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'TRENDING JEFF BEZOS THANKS AMAZON EMPLOYEES AFTER SPACE FLIGHT: "YOU GUYS PAID FOR THIS"'.

node.text: The billionaire space race hit another milestone on July 20 when Jeff Bezos made it to space and back in a 10-minute-long flight in the first-ever human flight on Blue Origin’s New Shepard Rocket Ship. Upon landing with his crew, the Amazon founder spoke to the media about how his experience “exceeded” his expectations and how space exploration is vital to keeping society aligned with caring about the environment. Most notably, Bezos took the time to thank not only Amazon’s employees but its customers, acknowledging that their support made Tuesday’s voyage possible. Head to our link in bio to learn more about what Bezos had to say once he returned back to Earth.

node.text:
@alanabranston and @alikriegs hope to see more non-technical entrepreneurs feel empowered to follow their dreams. “I think a lot of people, women especially, feel boxed out of certain prospects because there’s a lot of messaging out there saying you have to be a technical founder or engineer to build this kind of system,” Kriegsman says. “But so much of building a successful business is raising your hand and asking for help.” 

@bulletin.co co-founders Alana Branston and Ali Kriegsman's shared passion for independent brands and the world of content marketing helped fuel their company's 30% month-over-month organic growth last year. Link in bio for the full article.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Entrepreneur on July 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'TRENDING BLUE ORIGIN BEZOS' ROCKETSHIP WILL LAUNCH 18-YEAR-OLD INTO SPACE, MAKING HISTORY'.

node.text: The billionaire space race wages onward as Amazon founder Jeff Bezos’ inaugural space flight is set to take place this Tuesday. The long-anticipated flight has garnered much public attention after an anonymous bidder paid a cool $28 million to snag the final seat aboard the flight. But due to “scheduling conflicts” on behalf of the bidder, the seat will now go to 18-year-old Oliver Daemen who will make history by being the youngest astronaut to go to space. Visit our link in bio to learn about Daemen and why he’ll be the one taking the coveted spot.

node.text: Consistent hard work leads to success.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Entrepreneur on July 15, 2021 tagging @paul_hedrick, and @tecovas. May be an image of 1 person, footwear and indoor.

node.text:
Native Texan @paul_hedrick, like many entrepreneurs, landed on his million-dollar idea by creating a product he wanted but couldn't find. During a stint working in private equity in Greenwich, Connecticut, he took to wearing cowboy boots to work to stand out in a sea of loafers and feel closer to his Texas roots. But those boots cost around $600, and Hedrick was convinced the $3 billion Western boot industry could use some shaking up — why wasn't there someone cutting out the middlemen and selling well-priced boots straight to consumers? @tecovas was born. 

That was 2014, and in the seven years since then, Hedrick has relocated to Austin, launched Tecovas, expanded into new product lines and opened retail outposts in Austin, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, San Antonio and, as of June, Aspen, Colorado.

Learn more about his morning routine, his favorite business book, favorite piece of leadership advice and more in our link in bio.
